Credit Chronicles: Exploring Cardholder Behavior


Authors: Tulasi Thotakura, Sai Krishna Paila, Gourab Mukherjee
Keywords- Credit Card, Exploratory data analysis, Utilization Ratio


Abstract

In the “Credit Chronicles: Exploring Cardholder Behavior” project, our team, is dedicated to investigate the interactions between 10,127 clients and a financial institution. The data set at our disposal encompasses a wide array of client attributes, including age, income category, and credit card preferences. We aim to discern distinct customer segments through the process of customer segmentation, seeking to understand how these attributes combine to define unique client groups. Our research is also focused on the analysis of transaction patterns and behaviors across various income categories, which enables us to gain valuable insights into typical client practices. Furthermore, we delve into the intricate relationship between a client’s average utilization ratio and their credit limit, with a particular emphasis on encouraging responsible credit utilization. One of the central objectives of our project is to pinpoint the primary drivers of client attrition. Our aim is to categorize these factors based on elements such as age, credit utilization, or contact frequency. In addition, we explore the correlation between client income categories and attrition rates, with the ultimate goal of devising strategies to retain clients in lower income brackets. The “Credit Chronicles” data set, hosted on our GitHub repository, serves as an invaluable resource for this research, providing a robust foundation for an in-depth exploration of client profiles and behaviors. The findings we uncover are anticipated to provide insights that can significantly enhance the overall banking experience, and we believe they will prove to be instrumental for financial institutions in their mission to better serve their clients.

Introduction

In the era of evolving financial services and dynamic customer expectations, the “Credit Chronicles” project stands at the forefront of analyzing and optimizing the client experience. With a dataset encompassing over 10,000 individuals and their interactions with a financial institution, the project unveils a treasure trove of insights into clients’ behavior and preferences. This comprehensive dataset provides a rich tapestry of demographic information, including age, gender, education level, marital status, and income category. Moreover, it delves deep into credit card usage patterns, revealing details about credit limits, transaction behaviors, and card categories. The dataset doesn’t stop at the surface level; it also delves into the dynamics of banking relationships, shedding light on the total number of relationships and months of inactivity. This wealth of data offers an exceptional opportunity to unravel the mysteries of client profiles and behaviors, serving as a foundation for a holistic analysis of factors influencing banking relationships, credit card usage patterns, and, significantly, client attrition. The project aspires to understand the nuanced intricacies of client segments, transaction behaviors across diverse income categories, the correlation between credit utilization and credit limits, the factors underpinning client attrition, and strategies to retain clients, particularly those in lower income categories.

As the project unfolds, the team’s data preprocessing efforts have been meticulous, including data loading, type validation, and the management of null values. Further statistical analyses, such as t-tests, chi-squared tests, and correlation assessments, have revealed invaluable insights, uncovering distinctions and relationships that hold the potential to reshape the financial landscape. “Credit Chronicles” is poised to answer critical questions and provide actionable recommendations to enhance the overall banking experience. By harnessing the power of data and the art of statistical analysis, this project seeks to revolutionize banking, offering clients personalized services and ensuring that financial institutions remain at the forefront of an ever-evolving industry.

Data and methodology

The “Credit Chronicles” project is built upon a dataset acquired from Kaggle, which offers insights into the financial behaviors of 10,127 clients and their interactions with a financial institution. This dataset includes a range of client attributes, spanning age, gender, education level, marital status, and income categories. Additionally, it delves into credit card usage patterns, encompassing credit limits, transaction amounts, and card categories, while also shedding light on banking relationships, such as the total number of relationships and periods of inactivity.

To ensure data readiness, the team has diligently conducted data preprocessing tasks, which encompass the verification of data types, handling of null values, and the structuring of data for subsequent analysis. In the methodological approach, a suite of statistical techniques, such as t-tests, chi-squared tests, and correlation analyses, are applied to uncover hidden patterns, correlations, and distinctions within the dataset. With research objectives centered around customer segmentation, transaction behaviors in different income categories, the factors contributing to client attrition, credit utilization patterns, and the relationship between income categories and client churn, this project aims to provide actionable insights that can inform strategic decisions and enhance the overall banking experience.

EDA of Numerical Variables

The exploratory data analysis (EDA) conducted on the dataset focuses on its numerical variables, shedding light on key financial attributes of the customers. Among these variables, “Customer_Age,” “Total_Trans_Amt,” “Total_Trans_Ct,” and “Credit_Limit” are examined in detail. By employing histograms and density curves, the EDA reveals critical insights into the financial behaviors and characteristics of the customers.The “Customer_Age” histogram, using a bin width of 3, provides a comprehensive view of the age distribution within the customer base. This visualization helps identify whether the customer population is skewed towards a particular age group or exhibits distinct gaps or anomalies in age distribution. Such insights can guide targeted marketing and product development efforts.

Moving to transaction-related attributes, the histograms for “Total_Trans_Amt” and “Total_Trans_Ct” are essential for understanding customer spending patterns. With bin widths of 500 and 7, respectively, these visualizations unveil the distribution of total transaction amounts and counts. They are instrumental in pinpointing concentration ranges and detecting potential outliers within the transaction data. This knowledge can inform strategies for customer engagement, loyalty programs, and credit limit adjustments. Overall, the EDA of the numerical variables lays the groundwork for more advanced data analysis, empowering data scientists and business analysts to make data-driven decisions and tailor financial offerings to better serve the customer base.

Segmentation

A.Customer Segmentation

The customer segmentation analysis, as presented, offers a valuable perspective on the credit card customer base. It leverages essential attributes such as “Customer_Age,” “Income_Category,” and “Card_Category” to create distinct customer segments based on age and income. These segments encompass various customer profiles, categorized as “Young High Income,” “Middle Age High Income,” “Senior High Income,” “Young Low Income,” “Middle Age Low Income,” and “Senior Low Income.” Each segment represents a unique combination of age and income characteristics, providing insights that financial institutions like me can use to customize services and marketing strategies according to the diverse needs and preferences of these customer groups.

The scatter plot visualization, which highlights the distribution of these segments within the dataset, is a powerful tool for understanding how different age and income profiles are represented among credit card customers. By plotting “Customer_Age” against “Income_Category” and color-coding data points by their respective segments, this graph offers an insightful snapshot of the customer landscape. Additionally, the computation of summary statistics for each segment, including average age and income, further enhances the understanding of these distinct customer groups. This detailed customer segmentation analysis is pivotal for financial institutions in developing targeted marketing campaigns, designing personalized financial products, and ultimately enhancing customer satisfaction by addressing their specific financial needs.

Outlier Detection and removal

The outlier detection and removal process is a crucial step in data preprocessing to maintain the overall quality of the dataset. It contributes to the reliability and accuracy of any subsequent analyses or modeling efforts. In the context of credit card data, outliers can often indicate unusual or irregular transactions or customer profiles that could skew statistical summaries or predictive models. Addressing outliers in attributes such as “Customer_Age,” “Credit_Limit,” “Months_on_book,” “Total_Revolving_Bal,” “Total_Trans_Amt,” “Total_Trans_Ct,” “Avg_Open_To_Buy,” and “Avg_Utilization_Ratio” is especially important as these variables play a fundamental role in assessing customer creditworthiness and financial behavior. By replacing outlier values with missing data indicators (NA), we effectively mitigate their influence on the data, promoting more accurate and reliable insights for decision-makers in the financial industry.

Furthermore, the removal of outliers is essential for maintaining data consistency, improving the generalizability of machine learning models, and aligning financial products and services with the true financial profiles of customers. Outliers can skew the distribution of data, leading to misleading conclusions and hindering the ability to identify trends and patterns that are representative of the majority of customers. By systematically handling outliers, financial institutions can ensure that their analyses and models are more robust, and the decisions based on these insights are better suited to meet the diverse financial needs of their customer base, ultimately enhancing customer satisfaction and risk management strategies.

Standard Deviation

The computation of standard deviations for various attributes within the credit card dataset is a fundamental statistical analysis that provides insights into the data’s dispersion and variability. This measure of dispersion is particularly valuable in the financial industry as it aids in understanding the distribution of important attributes such as “Customer_Age,” “Credit_Limit,” “Months_on_book,” “Avg_Open_To_Buy,” “Avg_Utilization_Ratio,” “Total_Revolving_Bal,” “Total_Trans_Amt,” and “Total_Trans_Ct.” The standard deviation indicates the degree to which these variables deviate from their respective means. For instance, a higher standard deviation implies greater variability or spread in the data, while a lower standard deviation suggests more concentrated values around the mean. By calculating and summarizing the standard deviations for these attributes, financial analysts can gain valuable insights into the level of risk and variability associated with different aspects of customer credit profiles.

Moreover, the standard deviations can inform data-driven decision-making processes within the financial sector. They help in identifying attributes that exhibit significant variations, potentially indicating areas where financial institutions need to apply more focused risk management strategies or tailor their services accordingly. Additionally, standard deviations play a pivotal role in portfolio management and assessing the volatility of financial products. Understanding the spread of key variables like “Credit_Limit” or “Total_Trans_Amt” is essential for pricing models and assessing customer creditworthiness. By effectively interpreting and utilizing the standard deviations of these attributes, financial institutions can make informed decisions to enhance their risk assessment processes and better serve their customers.

Analyzing Gender Differences in Total Transaction Amount

In this analysis, we aim to investigate potential differences in the total transaction amount based on gender among credit card holders. A two-sample t-test is performed to compare the means of total transaction amounts for male and female cardholders. The results of the t-test will determine whether there is a statistically significant difference in transaction amounts between these two gender groups.

The outcome of this analysis provides insights into whether gender plays a significant role in influencing the total transaction amounts for credit card holders. Financial institutions can utilize this information to tailor their marketing strategies, develop gender-specific offers, or address any gender-based variations in transaction behavior. By understanding the gender-specific patterns in total transaction amounts, credit card providers can enhance their customer engagement and satisfaction strategies to better serve the diverse needs of their clientele.

Analyzing Income Category for Credit Card Churn

In this analysis, we focus on exploring the relationship between income category and credit card churn status. A contingency table is created to cross-tabulate these two variables. This table summarizes the distribution of credit card holders across different income categories and their corresponding churn statuses. The chi-square test is then conducted to evaluate the statistical significance of any association between these variables.

The results of the chi-square test provide valuable insights into whether there is a statistically significant relationship between income category and credit card churn. This analysis is essential for financial institutions, as it helps in understanding whether certain income groups are more likely to experience credit card churn. Such insights can inform targeted strategies and initiatives to retain customers, particularly those in income categories with higher churn rates. By examining the relationship between income and churn, financial institutions can tailor their services and offers to reduce churn and enhance customer satisfaction.

Analysis of Contacts Count and Customer Attrition

This analysis involves conducting an independent samples t-test to examine the differences in the number of contacts made in the last 12 months (Contacts_Count_12_mon) between two groups: attrited customers and existing customers. The t-test is utilized to determine whether there is a statistically significant difference in the mean number of contacts between these groups. The results of the t-test provide valuable insights into whether the frequency of contacts made with customers is related to their attrition status. By understanding such relationships, financial institutions can optimize their customer engagement strategies and adjust contact frequencies to improve customer retention rates and overall satisfaction.

Income Category and Attrition Analysis

This analysis involves investigating the relationship between income categories and customer attrition within the credit card customer base. A contingency table is constructed to examine the distribution of customers across different income categories (ranging from less than $40K to greater than $120K) concerning their attrition status. Additionally, a chi-squared test is conducted to determine whether there is a statistically significant association between income category and attrition. The outcome of this analysis helps identify whether certain income categories are more prone to customer attrition than others. Furthermore, the attrition rate for each income category is calculated to provide insights into the proportion of customers who have attrited in relation to the total number of customers in that income bracket. This information is valuable for financial institutions to tailor retention strategies and services to specific income categories, ultimately reducing customer attrition rates.

Conclusion

In this comprehensive analysis of credit card customer data, we explored various aspects of customer behavior, segmentation, and influential factors. The study initiated by examining categorical variables such as attrition flags and income categories, shedding light on customer attrition rates and the distribution of income levels within the customer base. Subsequently, we conducted a t-test to evaluate gender-based differences in the average utilization ratio, revealing that there is no statistically significant variance between male and female credit card holders in this aspect. Furthermore, we utilized chi-square tests to examine the relationships between income categories and attrition flags, providing valuable insights into how income level affects customer attrition rates. The outcomes of these statistical analyses empower financial institutions to develop tailored strategies for customer retention based on income categories.

We also delved into numerical variables like age, credit limits, transaction behavior, and more. Exploratory data analysis, outlier detection, and correlation analysis helped uncover relationships and trends within the dataset. For instance, we identified high correlations between attributes like total revolving balance and average utilization ratio, providing actionable insights for customer engagement and targeted offers. The standard deviation analysis offered a more in-depth understanding of the dataset’s numerical variability, facilitating better-informed decision-making. In conclusion, this data-driven analysis has equipped financial institutions with valuable information to refine their marketing, product development, and customer retention strategies. By understanding customer behavior, preferences, and segmentation, credit card providers can enhance customer satisfaction, reduce attrition rates, and foster stronger relationships with their clientele. This study underscores the importance of data-driven decision-making in the ever-evolving landscape of the financial services industry.
